com.apriori.collections

Class LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
        • com.apriori.collections.AbstractLockFreeBlockingQueue<E>
          • com.apriori.collections.LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element held in the queue
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, BlockingQueue<E>, Queue<E>

    public class LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue<E>
extends AbstractLockFreeBlockingQueue<E>
    A blocking queue that is backed by an array and is lock-free. Since it is lock-free, it does not support growing the underlying array, so the capacity must be provided at the time the queue is constructed.

    Because it is lock-free, it does not support interior removes. So calls to remove(Object), removeAll(Collection), retainAll(Collection), Collection.removeIf(Predicate), and Iterator.remove() will throw UnsupportedOperationException. This makes the queue most suitable for custom usages that will never attempt an interior remove. Since ThreadPoolExecutor has several operations (including the execute method) that may attempt an interior remove, this queue is not quite appropriate for that use. To use as a work queue for an executor, use executorWorkQueue(int).

      • remainingCapacity

        public int remainingCapacity()

      • executorWorkQueue

        public static LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue<Runnable> executorWorkQueue(int capacity)
        Returns a blocking queue that is suitable for use as the work queue for a ThreadPoolExecutor and is backed by a LockFreeArrayBlockingQueue. Since interior removes are not supported, attempts to perform such a removal will instead change the task into a no-op. This means that interior removes cannot be used to free up capacity in the queue. Only worker threads de-queueing items can make room for new tasks.

        Removed items will be elided when querying the queue, for example from Queue.peek(), Queue.poll(), or Collection.iterator(). However, they will still be reflected in the Collection.size() and BlockingQueue.remainingCapacity(). The no-op tasks are actually cleaned up during operations that remove tasks from the head of the queue.

        Parameters:
        capacity - the maximum capacity of the work queue, which is allocated all up front
        Returns:
        a blocking queue that is suitable for use as a work queue
